04484nam a22005895i 9780773596450DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735964507 a10.1515/97807735964502doi  a(DE-B1597)655690  a(OCoLC)875729394  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX4659.C2bP42 2014 7aHIS0060102bisacsh04a282.092/2712231 aPearson, Timothy G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBecoming Holy in Early Canada /cTimothy G. Pearson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource :b4 b&w photos, 2 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Cult of the Saints and Early Canada -- tEvangelism: Martyrdom -- tEvangelism: Indigenous Holiness -- tCharity: Domesticating Holiness -- tAsceticism: Making a New Culture -- tMiracles: Social Dramas and Community Bonds -- tHagiography: Writing Memory -- tConclusion -- tHoly Persons of New France -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecent years have witnessed a revival of interest in holy figures in Canada. From the reputations of popes John Paul II and Benedict XVI as prolific saint-makers to the canonization of two figures associated with Canada - Brother André Bessette in 2010 and Kateri Tekakwitha in 2012 - saints are suddenly in the news and a topic of conversation. In Becoming Holy in Early Canada, Timothy Pearson explores the roots of sanctity in Canada to discover why reputations for holiness developed in the early colonial period and how saints were made in the local and immediate contexts of everyday life. Pearson weaves together the histories of well-known figures such as Marie de l'Incarnation with those of largely forgotten local saints such as lay brother and carpenter Didace Pelletier and the Algonquin martyr Joseph Onaharé. Adopting an approach that draws on performance theory, ritual studies, and lived religion, he unravels the expectations, interactions, and negotiations that constituted holy performances. Because holy reputations developed over the course of individuals' lifetimes and in after-death relationships with local faith communities through belief in miracles, holy lives are best read as local, embedded, and contextualized histories. Placing colonial holy figures between the poles of local expectation and the universal Catholic theology of sanctity, Becoming Holy in Early Canada shows how reputations developed and individuals became local saints long before they came to the attention of the church in Rome.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian hagiography. 0aChristian saintsxCultxHistoryxCanada. 0aChristian saintsxCultzCanadaxHistory. 0aChristian saintsxHistoryxCanada. 0aChristian saintszCanadaxHistory. 0aHolinessxCatholic ChurchxHistory of doctrines. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359645040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773596450423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773596450/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles